    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Working Families, Going Without</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Roslyn Powell letter on Sept 13 article scores New York City's failure to use up-to-date income guidelines for child care subsidies</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Family Needs Far Exceed the Official Poverty Line'' (news article, Sept. 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Family Needs Far Exceed the Official Poverty Line'' (news article, Sept. 13):</p>
        <p>New York City families receiving child care subsidies face a double whammy. Not only are child care co-payment fees based on a nationwide federal poverty level, that level is more than 10 years old. Despite state regulations requiring New York City to update its fee scale yearly to determine child care co-payments, the scale currently being used is based on 1990 poverty levels.</p>
        <p>As a result, these families have either been wrongly deemed ineligible for child care subsides or have been paying child care fees far in excess of what they can afford.</p>
        <p>Given the critical importance of child care to the ability of any family to work and become self-sufficient, is it too much to ask that New York City follow the law?</p>
        <p>ROSLYN POWELL  New York, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is staff attorney, NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
